  "reason_thou": "1. **Understanding the Issue**: The assertion failure occurs
because the `removeInstructionsAndOperands` function attempts to erase an
instruction (`I`) that still has active users. The assertion checks that either
the instruction has no users (`use_empty()`) or all its users are marked as
deleted (`isDeleted`). However, the evaluation shows that some users of the
instruction are not marked as deleted, leading to the assertion failure.\n\n2.
**Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The log indicates that the SLP vectorizer is
attempting to vectorize a reduction tree. The issue arises during the cleanup
phase, where instructions are removed from the IR. The `isDeleted` function is
expected to return `true` for all users of an instruction being erased, but this
is not the case for some deeply nested `select` instructions.\n\n3. **Root Cause
Analysis**: The root cause is that the `isDeleted` function does not correctly
identify all users of the instruction as deleted. This could happen if the
deletion marking logic does not propagate correctly through the chain of
dependent instructions. Specifically, the `select` instructions in the reduction
tree are not being marked as deleted, even though they are part of the tree being
vectorized.\n\n4. **Proposed Edit Points**:\n   - Edit the assertion at lines
2748-2753 in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp` to include
additional logging or checks to identify why `isDeleted` is returning `false` for
some users. This will help diagnose the propagation issue.\n   - Ensure that all
instructions in the reduction tree are marked as deleted before attempting to
erase them. This may involve modifying the logic that marks instructions as
deleted to handle nested `select` instructions more robustly.\n\n5.
**Conclusion**: The fix involves ensuring that all instructions in the reduction
tree are correctly marked as deleted before they are erased. This will prevent
the assertion failure and allow the SLP vectorizer to complete successfully.",
